Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

We are removing popup handling from the platform plugins in general (see for example 65c9acc5f529689f609ebec5e6aae59a171982e4). 

However this is a special case: the wasm platform plugin is also the window manager, so we might have to close popups if/when Qt did not handle the mouse event.

messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

wow, ehum... if idealThreadCount() can change at any time, I don't know where to start...

- idealThreadCountChanged()?
- will QThreadPool adapt dynamically?
- [ChangeLog], please

I'm a bit worried that code expects this to never change and e.g. call it twice to allocate two arrays, assuming they're the same size:

    auto threads = std::vector<std::thread>(QThread::idealThreadCount());
    // idealThreadCount() changes here
    auto results = std::vector<MyResultType>(QThread::idealThreadCount());

that's a bit like creating a QDateTime from {currentDate(), currentTime()}, except that will at most be wrong by 24h, not run into UB...

Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

> - idealThreadCountChanged()?

Can't implement this short of polling. We're not notified that our CPU affinity set has been changed from the outside.

But it's extremely rare that it gets done.

The worst case scenario we're likely to see is that someone creates a thread inside the process and sets the affinity to one or a few logical processors in the system, for some reason. Then the value is different in that thread compared to other threads (on Linux; the FreeBSD API appears to be the process, not the thread).

> - will QThreadPool adapt dynamically?

No and I don't see how we could do that.

> - [ChangeLog], please

Done.

> I'm a bit worried that code expects this to never change and e.g. call it twice to allocate two arrays, assuming they're the same size:
> 
>     auto threads = std::vector<std::thread>(QThread::idealThreadCount());
>     // idealThreadCount() changes here
>     auto results = std::vector<MyResultType>(QThread::idealThreadCount());
> 
> that's a bit like creating a QDateTime from {currentDate(), currentTime()}, except that will at most be wrong by 24h, not run into UB...

I understand.

But I find this is an improvement compared to the prior solution. Before:

 $ LC_ALL=C taskset 3 strace -E QT_MESSAGE_PATTERN= -s 256 ./tst_qthread -o /dev/null idealThreadCount 2>&1 | sed -n '/initTestCase/,/idealThreadCount/p'
write(4, "PASS   : tst_QThread::initTestCase()\n", 37) = 37
openat(AT_FDCWD, "/sys/devices/system/cpu/online", O_RDONLY|O_CLOEXEC) = 5
read(5, "0-7\n", 1024)                  = 4
close(5)                                = 0
openat(AT_FDCWD, "/sys/devices/system/cpu/online", O_RDONLY|O_CLOEXEC) = 5
read(5, "0-7\n", 1024)                  = 4
close(5)                                = 0
access("/home/tjmaciei/obj/qt/installed/lib64", F_OK) = 0
openat(AT_FDCWD, "/home/tjmaciei/obj/qt/installed/share/qt6/qtlogging.ini", O_RDONLY|O_CLOEXEC) = -1 ENOENT (No such file or directory)
statx(AT_FDCWD, "/home/tjmaciei/.config/QtProject/qtlogging.ini", AT_STATX_SYNC_AS_STAT|AT_NO_AUTOMOUNT, STATX_ALL, 0x7ffc1e26a810) = -1 ENOENT (No such file or directory)
statx(AT_FDCWD, "/home/tjmaciei/.config/kdedefaults/QtProject/qtlogging.ini", AT_STATX_SYNC_AS_STAT|AT_NO_AUTOMOUNT, STATX_ALL, 0x7ffc1e26a810) = -1 ENOENT (No such file or directory)
statx(AT_FDCWD, "/etc/xdg/QtProject/qtlogging.ini", AT_STATX_SYNC_AS_STAT|AT_NO_AUTOMOUNT, STATX_ALL, 0x7ffc1e26a810) = -1 ENOENT (No such file or directory)
statx(AT_FDCWD, "/usr/etc/xdg/QtProject/qtlogging.ini", AT_STATX_SYNC_AS_STAT|AT_NO_AUTOMOUNT, STATX_ALL, 0x7ffc1e26a810) = -1 ENOENT (No such file or directory)
write(4, "QDEBUG : tst_QThread::idealThreadCount() Ideal thread count: 8\n", 63) = 63

After:

 $ LC_ALL=C taskset 3 strace -E QT_MESSAGE_PATTERN= -s 256 ./tst_qthread -o /dev/null idealThreadCount 2>&1 | sed -n '/initTestCase/,/idealThreadCount/p'
write(4, "PASS   : tst_QThread::initTestCase()\n", 37) = 37
sched_getaffinity(0, 128, [0, 1])       = 8
sched_getaffinity(0, 128, [0, 1])       = 8
access("/home/tjmaciei/obj/qt/qt6/qtbase/lib", F_OK) = 0
openat(AT_FDCWD, "/home/tjmaciei/obj/qt/qt6/qtbase/qtlogging.ini", O_RDONLY|O_CLOEXEC) = -1 ENOENT (No such file or directory)
statx(AT_FDCWD, "/home/tjmaciei/.config/QtProject/qtlogging.ini", AT_STATX_SYNC_AS_STAT|AT_NO_AUTOMOUNT, STATX_ALL, 0x7ffd1428c4b0) = -1 ENOENT (No such file or directory)
statx(AT_FDCWD, "/home/tjmaciei/.config/kdedefaults/QtProject/qtlogging.ini", AT_STATX_SYNC_AS_STAT|AT_NO_AUTOMOUNT, STATX_ALL, 0x7ffd1428c4b0) = -1 ENOENT (No such file or directory)
statx(AT_FDCWD, "/etc/xdg/QtProject/qtlogging.ini", AT_STATX_SYNC_AS_STAT|AT_NO_AUTOMOUNT, STATX_ALL, 0x7ffd1428c4b0) = -1 ENOENT (No such file or directory)
statx(AT_FDCWD, "/usr/etc/xdg/QtProject/qtlogging.ini", AT_STATX_SYNC_AS_STAT|AT_NO_AUTOMOUNT, STATX_ALL, 0x7ffd1428c4b0) = -1 ENOENT (No such file or directory)
write(4, "QDEBUG : tst_QThread::idealThreadCount() Ideal thread count: 2\n", 63) = 63

The previous solution has two problems:
* it returns 8 when the current process can only run two threads in parallel before they start stealing CPU time from each other

> I think I'd still prefer new API for this, not shoehorning it into idealThreadCount(). 

I think this change makes idealThreadCount() correct. See the example of taskset'ting to 2 threads from the command-line: without this change, idealThreadCount() would return 8 or 96 or whatever, so the user code might launch that many threads and they'd all be competing for the same 2 logical CPUs that the process has affinity to.

I also need to investigate Windows at some point. I think the process is always limited to 64 at most, however many logical processors the system may have, due to a limitation of the OS.

> I still don't like your poking into the documented-to-be-opaque data structure, too.

Fair enough, it's poking at it. The kernel ABI in both cases is a plain bit field, though.

FreeBSD doesn't have CPU_ALLOC() and CPU_FREE(), so it would need to be #ifdef'ed for FreeBSD, meaning I'd still have this QVarLengthARray. That makes the code more fragile because we don't often build for FreeBSD (KDE has a CI, though).

Therefore, I simply refuse to make my code more complex for a situation that does not happen today, has negligible chance of ever happening in the future, for systems that don't exist today and where Qt is unlikely to ever be run on for 20 years.

I agree. But it also sets up idealThreadCount() users for nasty surprises. E.g., it seems it's quite common for mobile apps to bind threads to only the Little or only the Big cores of a Big/Little system. If you call QThreadPool::globalInstance() from main(), you get, say, 8 threads (which is probably fine), if you call it from some other thread that was pinned to Big cores, you only get, say, 4. That's surprising, to say the least. 

Therefore, I suggest to add new API for this. It no longer is a per-process property, it's a per-thread property, so it should be query-able that way. idealThreadCount() should stay constant for all threads in a process.

I'll need someone to confirm this is done via CPU affinity on Linux. I have absolutely zero experience in this domain to say one way or another. For all I know, it could be done entirely on the scheduler without changing the process' affinity.

The in-progress scheduler for Intel hybrid CPUs will be like that. You can set the affinity, but in the majority of cases you expect the scheduler to simply select the best for you based on what your current (and maybe historical) workload is, as well as whatever else is happening in the system.

BTW, do note this code is !Q_OS_ANDROID.

> Therefore, I suggest to add new API for this. It no longer is a per-process property, it's a per-thread property, so it should be query-able that way. idealThreadCount() should stay constant for all threads in a process.

It's a per-thread feature that can only be obtained on Linux. On ANY other OS it won't work. And it's inherited, which is why the setting applies process-wide for the vast majority of cases.

I don't think that's a good API.

Patch Set 6:

Windows has both SetProcessAffinityMask and SetThreadAffinityMask, but only  GetProcessAffinityMask <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/winbase/nf-winbase-getprocessaffinitymask>. The new API has the opposite split: getters for both thread and process, but setter only for the thread. Additionally, each thread is limited to a single processor group.

So for Windows and FreeBSD, we could return the count of the process-wide affinity mask. But on Linux we can't, because the kernel simply does not track that information. I don't know that using getpid() instead of 0 helps: that will get the main thread's affinity, which may or may not be the correct result.

I think the implementation as-is is correct, though. First, because changing the affinity mask of a thread is an unlikely case. Second, even when that is done, those threads usually don't call back to user code using Qt. Third, even if that did happen, QThread::idealThreadCount() is usually used to determine how many more threads to start from the current thread and the mask will be inherited by those threads, so it would be the correct value regardless.

Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

Do we (want to) guarantee that window minimum and maximum size is respected also when programmatically resizing a window, or is this an "assume the app knows better" situation?

Patch Set 2:

The QWindow::setMinimumSize() documentation states that "This is a hint to the window manager to prevent resizing below the specified size."

On the other hand, the QWidget::size property has "The size is adjusted if it lies outside the range defined by minimumSize() and maximumSize()."

So I'd say there is precedent for also making QWindow enforce min/max size when setting the size programatically.

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> The QWindow::setMinimumSize() documentation states that "This is a hint to the window manager to prevent resizing below the specified size."
> 
> On the other hand, the QWidget::size property has "The size is adjusted if it lies outside the range defined by minimumSize() and maximumSize()."
> 
> So I'd say there is precedent for also making QWindow enforce min/max size when setting the size programatically.

I'd agree. If not, a manual resize might end up giving the window a size that the window manager then barfs on when trying to interactively resize it, and other code in Qt that assumes that the size is within the min/max size might break as well.
